Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
specifyCellEdgeType(25.10)                          specifyCellEdgeType(25.10)

Name
       specifyCellEdgeType - Specifies edge type for cell edges as EDGETYPE in
       macro LEF

Syntax
       specifyCellEdgeType

       [-help]

       {-left  <edgeType> | -right <edgeType> | -top <edgeType> | -bottom <ed-
       geType> | -reset }

       [{-left <edgeType> | -right <edgeType>} [-cellRow <rowNumber>]]

       [{-left <edgeType> | -right <edgeType>} [-half {top | bottom}]]

       [{-top <edgeType> | -bottom <edgeType>} [-range {x y}]]

       [{-cell <cellName>} [-reset]]

       Specifies edge type for cell edges as EDGETYPE in macro LEF. It  allows
       to specify one edge at a time for a particular cell.

       To  ensure  the correct edge type specification, edge types asserted by
       specifyCellEdgeType command  should  be  pre-defined  by  the  specify-
       CellEdgeSpacing command.

       For example:

       specifyCellEdgeSpacing grp1 grp2 0.18

       specifyCellEdgeType -cell BUF1X -left grp1

       If  the edge type is specified without corresponding spacing rule, tool
       gives a warning and ignores the edge type specification.

Parameters
       -bottom <edgeType>
              Specifies an edge type on the bottom side.

       -cell <cellName>
              Specifies cell to which to add edge constraint.

       -cellRow <rowNumber>
              Specifies the row number for horizontal edge type.

              You can define different edge types for  each  row  of  multiple
              height cells using -cellRow.

              For example, there is triple height cell CKBUF.

              The following commands define different edge types for different
              rows of the CKBUF cell.

              specifyCellEdgeType -cell CKBUF -right grp1 -cellRow 1

              specifyCellEdgeType -cell CKBUF -right grp2 -cellRow 2

              In  the  above example, grp1 is applied to the first row (bottom
              row) of the right edge, grp2 is applied to  the  second  row  of
              right  edge,  and no specific edge type is defined for the third
              row of right edge and is of DEFAULT type.

              The legal value of -cellRow is from 1 to n, where n is the  num-
              ber of cell height of the cell.

       -half {top bottom}
              Defines  the  edge types corresponding to the top or bottom half
              of the cell.

              The following example associates the edge type 'grp1'  with  the
              bottom row, top half of the multi-height cell SDFF8:

              specifyCellEdgeType -cell SDFF8 -right grp1 -cellRow 1 -half top

       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes type and default in-
              formation for each specifyCellEdgeType parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command: man specifyCellEdgeType

       -left <edgeType>
              Defines the edge types corresponding to the top or  bottom  half
              of the cell.

              The  following  example associates the edge type 'grp1' with the
              bottom row, top half of the multi-height cell SDFF8.

              specifyCellEdgeType -cell SDFF8 -right grp1 -cellRow 1 -half top

       -range {<x> <y>}
              Specifies the range for the vertical edge type.

              The range for the vertical edge type can also be negative.

              The following example defines a partial range of  an  edge  that
              the  type should be labeled.This could only be defined on TOP or
              BOTTOM edges.

              specifyCellEdgeType -cell A -top GROUP1 -range 0 0.1

              specifyCellEdgeType -cell A -bottom GROUP1 -range 0 0.1

              specifyCellEdgeType -cell A -top GROUP2 -range 0.2 0.3

              specifyCellEdgeType -cell A -top GROUP3 -range 0.15 0.25

       -reset Resets the specified cell constraint to the LEF status.

       -right <edgeType>
              Specifies an edge type on the right side.

       -top <edgeType>
              Specifies an edge type on the top side.

Example
       The following commands specify one edge at a time for the BUF1X cell

              * specifyCellEdgeType -cell BUF1X -left grp1

              * specifyCellEdgeType -cell BUF1X -right grp1 -cellRow 1

              * specifyCellEdgeType -cell BUF1X -right grp1 -cellRow 2

